<a name="arabic-fonts"></a>
<h4>Arabic Fonts</h4>
<p>
The procedure to get Internet Explorer/Firefox/Opera to render the arabic fonts properly in a 
clean Windows installation appears to be:
<ul>
  <li>Go to Start - Settings - Control Panel - Regional Options
  <li>Tick the box 'Arabic' at 'Language settings for the system' and click OK
  <li>It will now need the Windows Installation disk to install the arabic fonts.
  <li>Reboot to enable the fonts
</ul>

<p>In Linux (Kubuntu Fiesty Fawn), there seem to be 2 options:
<ul>
  <li>Konqueror seems to be the only one capable of displaying readable arabic text without any extra font installations. The
    fonts doesn't look very nice though.
  <li>You can manually copy the Windows 2000 Arabic fonts in "C:\Windows\Fonts" from a windows installation to the linux fonts 
  directory such as /usr/share/fonts/truetype/win2k-arabic-fonts/. Here is a list of the files you would need to copy:
  <pre>
  andlso.ttf
  artrbdo.ttf
  artro.ttf
  simpbdo.ttf
  simpfxo.ttf
  simpo.ttf
  tradbdo.ttf
  trado.ttf
  </pre>
  After they have been copied, both Konqueror and Firefox seem to be able to display the arabic text the same as Internet Explorer.
</ul>
  
  
